"""
MKT Context Commentary — Joshua chapters 15–17
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-joshua-15-17.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/joshua.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/joshua.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Boundary descriptions: treated with ANE land-survey format context (comparable to
  Egyptian administrative texts on Canaan; the format is legal, not merely geographic)
- Caleb / Othniel / Achsah narrative (ch15:13-19): full treatment — Caleb as Kenizzite,
  Othniel as first judge, Achsah's initiative as significant within patriarchal context
- Kiriath-sepher (v15): possibly a Bronze Age scribal center (the name means 'city of
  the scroll/book'); discussed briefly
- Zelophehad's daughters (ch17:3-6): applied case law from Num 27; women's inheritance rights
- Iron chariots (ch17:16): Late Bronze/Iron Age military technology; archaeological context
- City-list verses (ch15:20-62): brief but substantive context notes on the zone system
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing: existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]: existing[ch][v] = html

JOSHUA = {
  "15": {
    "1": "<p>Judah's allotment is the longest and most detailed in the book — befitting the leading tribe from whose line the Davidic dynasty would come. The boundary description follows the standard ANE land-survey genre: a continuous line traced around the perimeter, naming landmarks, watercourses, and ridgelines in sequence. Egyptian administrative texts from the New Kingdom period (c. 1550–1070 BCE) use an identical format to describe Canaan's city territories, confirming that this is a formal property-record genre, not a loose narrative description.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The southern boundary begins at the 'bay at the south end of the Dead Sea' — the Lisan Peninsula. The Dead Sea's southern tip was a recognized geographic anchor point in the ancient Near East; its extreme salinity and the eerie stillness of the region made it a memorable boundary marker. Edom's proximity to the south explains why Judah's southern border doubles as the Edomite-Israelite frontier.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The Ascent of Akrabbim ('scorpion pass') is identified with the Nahal Zin pass, one of the steep ascents from the Arabah into the Negev plateau. Kadesh-barnea — the site of Israel's forty-year wilderness delay (Num 13:26; 20:1; Deut 1:46) — anchors the southwestern corner. Its inclusion grounds Judah's territorial claim in the wilderness history; the boundary runs through the very place where the first generation's failure occurred.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Wadi of Egypt (<em>naḥal miṣrayim</em>) is the Wadi el-Arish, the natural boundary between Canaan and Egypt throughout the ancient period. It marked the administrative border of Egyptian-controlled Canaan and appears as the southwestern limit of the promised land in Gen 15:18. The boundary terminates at 'the sea' (Mediterranean) — Judah's allotment does not extend to the coast but approaches it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The eastern boundary is simply the Dead Sea — the most natural of all geographic borders, requiring no surveyors' landmarks. The northern boundary begins at the Jordan's mouth (where it enters the Dead Sea) — the point where Judah meets Benjamin. The Dead Sea's role as eastern boundary explains Judah's later strategic relationship with the Transjordanian kingdoms: the sea both separated and connected them.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Beth-hoglah, Beth-arabah — sites in the lower Jordan valley at the boundary between Judah and Benjamin (Josh 18:21-22 lists both as Benjaminite). The Stone of Bohan son of Reuben — an unidentified landmark named for a Reubenite, suggesting Reubenite settlement or influence extended into the lower Jordan valley at some point in the pre-settlement period.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The boundary climbs from the Jordan valley to Debir (not the same Debir as v.15, but a northern landmark) and then to the Valley of Achor — the site of Achan's execution (Josh 7:24-26). The Valley of Achor's inclusion in the boundary description was memorable: a place of shame within Judah's territory. Hosea 2:15 will transform it into a 'door of hope,' inverting its association from covenant curse to covenant restoration.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Valley of Ben-hinnom (Hebrew: <em>gê ben-hinnôm</em>) is the ravine forming Jerusalem's southern boundary between Judah and Benjamin. This valley — later called Gehenna in Greek — became in the later monarchy the site of Molech child-sacrifice (2 Kgs 23:10; Jer 7:31) and subsequently the city's rubbish dump; by Second Temple times its name (<em>geenna</em>) had become the standard Jewish term for the place of final judgment. Jesus uses it in this sense (Matt 5:22,29,30; 10:28). The allotment boundary runs through what will become one of the Bible's most theologically charged landscapes.</p>",
    "9": "<p>From the hilltop to the spring of Nephtoah — likely modern Lifta, northwest of Jerusalem. The Nephtoah spring was a reliable water source in an otherwise dry limestone landscape. Mount Ephron and Baalah/Kiriath-jearim complete the northwestern boundary; Kiriath-jearim will become the ark's resting place for twenty years (1 Sam 7:1-2) before David brings it to Jerusalem — the boundary landmark is already freighted with future significance.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The boundary turns south from Kiriath-jearim to Mount Seir (not the Edomite Seir, but a Judahite ridge) and then to Beth-shemesh. Beth-shemesh ('house of the sun') was a major Shephelah city whose name preserves the Canaanite sun-deity worship that preceded Israel; it later receives the returning ark (1 Sam 6:9-20) and plays a role in the Philistine period.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The boundary reaches Ekron — one of the five Philistine cities — and then swings north to Shikkeron, Mount Baalah (a Canaanite high-place toponym embedded in the boundary), and Jabneel, reaching the sea. The coastal cities including Ekron remain outside Israelite possession; Judah's allotment is landlocked. The Philistine pentapolis occupies the very coast that would give Judah access to Mediterranean trade — their persistence (Josh 13:3) shapes Israelite economic and military history for centuries.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The western boundary is the coastline of the Great Sea — the Mediterranean. This verse closes the four-boundary description; the territory has been surveyed in all directions. The boundary formula's completion signals the legal recording of Judah's land title: what follows (city lists, vv.20-62) are the subsidiary properties within the boundary.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Caleb son of Jephunneh is identified as a Kenizzite — the Kenizzites appear in Gen 36:11,15,42 as an Edomite clan descended from Esau. Caleb is an ethnic outsider who has been fully incorporated into Judah, presumably through intermarriage or adoption into the tribe. His loyal report at Kadesh (Num 13:30; 14:24) earned him the specific promise of Hebron (Deut 1:36; Josh 14:9). The 'command to Joshua' that grants Caleb Hebron within Judah underscores that ethnic Israelite descent was not the sole criterion for land inheritance — covenant loyalty was.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The three Anakite leaders — Sheshai, Ahiman, and Talmai — are the same three named in Num 13:22 as the giants who terrified the scouts at Hebron. Forty-five years later, Caleb drives them out personally (Josh 14:10-12). The narrative closure is intentional: the specific fear that paralyzed the first generation (Num 13:28 — 'the descendants of Anak are there') is resolved by the specific faith of the one man who was never afraid. The three names also appear in Judg 1:10, suggesting this tradition was preserved in multiple sources.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Debir was formerly called Kiriath-sepher — 'city of the scroll/book' in Hebrew. This name may indicate that the city housed an administrative archive or scribal center; Bronze Age Canaan had several such centers where commercial and legal records were kept on clay tablets (Ugarit, Hazor). The name's preservation in the conquest account is one of the rare glimpses of Canaanite civic culture in Joshua — a city defined by its written records.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Caleb's offer — his daughter Achsah as wife to whoever conquers Kiriath-sepher — follows the ancient ANE convention of the military hero's reward, paralleled in Saul's offer of Merab (1 Sam 17:25; 18:17) and in Ugaritic epic tradition (the Kirta epic offers a daughter as reward for the warrior's service). The practice is not equivalent to modern bride-purchase but reflects the social economy of honor and alliance; the hero's marriage to the leader's daughter creates a political bond between the conqueror and the tribe.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Othniel son of Kenaz, Caleb's younger brother (or nephew — the Hebrew <em>ʾăḥî</em> can mean either) takes the city. He will reappear as the first judge (Judg 3:9-11) — the paradigm deliverer who delivers Israel from Cushan-rishathaim. The allotment narrative is already planting the seed of the judges cycle: the same man who wins Debir by military valor will be the prototype for Israel's deliverers. His Kenizzite ancestry parallels Caleb's — another outsider-incorporated member of Judah who demonstrates covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Achsah's approach to her father is striking for its initiative: she 'urges' (<em>wayyĕsîtĕhā</em> in some traditions is attributed to Othniel, but the context implies Achsah acts) and then dismounts her donkey in a formal gesture that signals she has a request to make. In ancient Near Eastern culture, dismounting before a superior was a gesture of respect and petition; Caleb's question ('what do you want?') acknowledges that she has made a formal approach. Her agency within the patriarchal framework is notable — she is the subject of her own request, not merely an object of the marriage arrangement.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Achsah's request — upper and lower springs (<em>gullōt ʿelyônôt</em> and <em>gullōt taḥtiyyôt</em>) — is agro-economically shrewd. The Negev land she has received is <em>ʾereṣ hannegeb</em> (dry southern land); without a reliable water source it cannot be farmed productively. Springs in the Negev were scarce and strategically vital. Her father grants both upper and lower springs — a double portion of water rights. The episode illustrates the practical dimension of land inheritance: boundary lines meant nothing without water access, and women with inherited land had the right to petition for what made it viable.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The introductory formula for Judah's city list: the list that follows (vv.21-62) is structured by geographic zone. The four zones — Negev (vv.21-32), Shephelah/lowlands (vv.33-47), hill country (vv.48-60), and wilderness (vv.61-62) — correspond to the four distinct ecological zones of Judah's territory. This is not a random enumeration but a systematic survey organized by terrain type, matching the geographic logic of the boundary description in vv.1-12.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Negev cities begin at the southern frontier. These settlements were the most exposed to Edomite and nomadic pressure; their names include places known from Abraham's wanderings (Beersheba appears in v.28). The Negev zone was semi-arid, supporting pastoral rather than intensive agriculture, and its towns were correspondingly smaller and less fortified than those in the Shephelah or hill country.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Kinah, Dimonah, Adadah — Negev cities whose locations remain uncertain. The preservation of obscure place names in an official list is evidence that this is a genuine administrative document, not a schematic inventory; a later editor would have known only the major cities.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Kedesh, Hazor (a southern Hazor, distinct from the northern city burned in ch.11), Ithnan — the southern tier continues. Multiple cities named 'Hazor' in different regions of Israel reflect the common Semitic place-name meaning 'enclosure' or 'settlement'; the geographic modifier distinguishes them in administrative use.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Ziph, Telem, Bealoth — all in the Negev. Ziph appears later as the location of David's wilderness refuge (1 Sam 23:14-15,24) and the site where the Ziphites betrayed him to Saul — the allotment geography shapes the narrative geography of the monarchy period.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Hazor-hadattah ('new Hazor'), Kerioth-hezron (also called Hazor) — compound names signaling either new foundations or administrative reorganization of settlements. Kerioth is notable: Judas Iscariot's surname 'Iscariot' may derive from <em>ʾîš qĕriyyôt</em> ('man of Kerioth'), potentially a Judahite city — though the identification is debated.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Amam, Shema, Moladah — Moladah was allocated to Simeon (Josh 19:2; 1 Chr 4:28), illustrating that Simeon's portion was entirely within Judah's territory (Josh 19:1,9), accounting for the overlap. The administrative integration of Simeon into Judah is already visible in the boundary descriptions.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Hazar-gaddah, Heshmon, Beth-pelet — desert frontier towns whose locations are disputed. The clustering of <em>hazar-</em> ('enclosure of') place names in the Negev reflects the settlement pattern of the Bronze Age: small defended enclosures, not large walled cities.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Hazar-shual, Beersheba, Biziothiah — Beersheba is the most significant city in this list: Abraham's covenant with Abimelech was sealed here (Gen 21:31-33), and it became the proverbial southern limit of Israel ('from Dan to Beersheba,' Judg 20:1). Its inclusion in the city list confirms the continuity between patriarchal-promise territory and the tribal allotment.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Baalah, Iim, Ezem — these three are also in Simeon's list (Josh 19:3; 1 Chr 4:29), again reflecting the administrative overlap between the two tribes. The name Baalah (feminine form of Baal) preserves a Canaanite divine name in the Negev landscape; the place may have been a Baal-worship site whose name Israel retained without renaming.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Eltolad, Chesil, Hormah — Hormah ('devoted thing,' from <em>ḥērem</em>) was the site of an early defeat (Num 14:45) and later a victory (Num 21:3); its name encodes the <em>ḥērem</em> theology in the landscape. The city appears in both Judah's and Simeon's lists (Josh 19:4), consistent with the Simeonite enclave pattern.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Ziklag, Madmannah, Sansannah — Ziklag is most famous as the Philistine city given to David by Achish king of Gath (1 Sam 27:6), where he staged his independent operations before becoming king. The note 'it belongs to the kings of Judah to this day' (1 Sam 27:6) implies a special royal status derived from David's tenure — the allotment and the monarchy intersect here.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Lebaoth, Shilhim, Ain, Rimmon — twenty-nine cities in the Negev zone (plus their villages). The total of twenty-nine cities closes the Negev section. These numbers, unlike the conquest summaries, are precise administrative counts — the kind of figure preserved in official land records rather than schematic narrative.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The Shephelah ('lowlands') zone begins — the broad transition zone between the coastal plain and the Judean hill country, strategically the most fought-over territory in Canaan's history. Egyptian, Philistine, Assyrian, Babylonian, and Roman armies all used the Shephelah passes (Aijalon, Sorek, Elah, Lachish) as access routes to the hill country. The Judahite cities here were buffer cities, repeatedly destroyed and rebuilt in the biblical period.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Zanoah, En-gannim, Tappuah, Enam — the northern Shephelah cities. These sites controlled access to the valleys leading into the hill country; their possession was essential to Judah's territorial integrity. The valley systems here (Aijalon, Sorek) are the routes used for the battles of ch.10 and later for the Philistine incursions of the Samson/Samuel period.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Jarmuth, Adullam, Socoh, Azekah — sites of key biblical narratives. Adullam's cave became David's fortress-refuge (1 Sam 22:1; 2 Sam 23:13). Socoh and Azekah define the Elah Valley — the site of David and Goliath (1 Sam 17:1). The allotment list maps the landscape of Israel's most famous later stories.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Shaaraim, Adithaim, Gederah, Gederothaim — fourteen cities in the first Shephelah sub-zone. Shaaraim ('two gates') appears in 1 Sam 17:52 as the road along which the Philistines fled after Goliath's defeat — narrative geography anchored in the allotment map.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Zenan, Hadashah, Migdal-gad — the southern Shephelah zone begins. Migdal-gad ('tower of Gad') is a compound with <em>migdal</em> (tower, fortress), reflecting the defensive architecture of Shephelah cities — multi-story towers visible across the plain for miles were characteristic of Late Bronze Age Canaanite urban design.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Dilean, Mizpeh, Joktheel — Mizpeh ('watchtower/lookout') is a common place name throughout Israel, reflecting the landscape's value for observation. Multiple Mizpehs create administrative ambiguity; the geographic context (Shephelah) distinguishes this one from the Benjamin Mizpeh and the Gilead Mizpeh.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Lachish, Bozkath, Eglon — Lachish is the most significant city in this section. As the dominant fortress of the Shephelah, it controlled the road from Egypt to Jerusalem; its destruction by Sennacherib in 701 BCE was depicted in a famous relief on his palace walls (now in the British Museum). The Lachish Letters (ANET 321-322), clay ostraca from just before the Babylonian conquest, are among the most important epigraphic finds from biblical Judah.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Cabbon, Lahmas, Kitlish — obscure sites whose locations remain uncertain. The preservation of these minor names in the official record underlines the document's archival character; a later composer would have known only Lachish and Eglon, not these smaller dependencies.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Gederoth, Beth-dagon, Naamah, Makkedah — Beth-dagon ('house of Dagon') preserves the name of the Philistine grain god in a Judahite city, reflecting the cultural fluidity of the Shephelah border zone where Israelite and Philistine territories overlapped. Dagon's temple in Ashdod is where the captured ark causes the idol to fall (1 Sam 5:2-5). Makkedah is the cave-site of the five kings' execution in ch.10:16-27.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Libnah, Ether, Ashan — Libnah was a Levitical city (Josh 21:13) and a site of priestly resistance; it revolted against Jehoram king of Judah (2 Kgs 8:22) and produced the mother of two kings (2 Kgs 23:31; 24:18). Its rebellion against a Davidic king shows the continuing political tensions between the Shephelah cities and the Jerusalem monarchy.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Iphtah, Ashnah, Nezib — these three are minor sites with no further OT narrative. The listing of otherwise-unknown settlements is the strong argument for the city lists' antiquity: they preserve administrative data that later periods would have no reason to invent.</p>",
    "44": "<p>Keilah, Achzib, Mareshah — Keilah is significant as the city David rescued from the Philistines (1 Sam 23:1-13) before the Ziphites' betrayal; the city's treachery in turn (1 Sam 23:12) shows that even rescued cities did not always maintain covenant loyalty to David. Mareshah appears in the Sennacherib campaign (Mic 1:15) and later in the Maccabean wars. Sixteen cities in this second Shephelah sub-zone.</p>",
    "45": "<p>Ekron with its towns and villages — one of the Philistine pentapolis, listed at the northern edge of Judah's Shephelah. Ekron's god Baal-zebub (2 Kgs 1:2-3,16) — 'lord of the flies' — was consulted by Ahaziah; the name became the NT form 'Beelzebul' (Matt 10:25; 12:24), a designation for Satan. The political reality behind the allotment: Ekron never came under Israelite control until the Maccabean period (1 Macc 10:89).</p>",
    "46": "<p>Ashdod and its territory — the cities west of Ekron toward the sea. Ashdod is one of the Philistine five; the ark of the covenant was brought there (1 Sam 5:1) and Dagon's temple destroyed by the ark's presence. The note 'all [the land] adjacent to Ashdod' acknowledges that while Ashdod is within Judah's claimed territory, it is not actually possessed — the gap between legal grant and actual control is built into the allotment document.</p>",
    "47": "<p>Ashdod and Gaza with their towns and villages, extending to the Wadi of Egypt. This is explicitly the Philistine coast — fully included in Judah's allotment, never actually possessed until after the Babylonian period. The breadth of the legal claim (all the way to the Wadi of Egypt) reflects the ideal boundaries of Gen 15:18 rather than the reality of Israelite settlement. The allotment is a title deed for what YHWH has given; actual possession is the ongoing work of covenant obedience.</p>",
    "48": "<p>The hill country zone begins — the central ridge of the Judean highlands, the core of Judah's actual settled territory. This terrain was heavily forested in the early Iron Age (Josh 17:15,18 reflects the reality) and required clearing for agriculture. The hill country's natural defenses (steep wadis, no chariot-accessible terrain) made it the part of Judah's allotment that was actually occupied and held; the Shephelah and coast remained contested.</p>",
    "49": "<p>Dannah, Kiriath-sannah/Debir — Debir (formerly Kiriath-sepher, v.15) appears here as a hill country city in the administrative list, separate from the narrative of its conquest in vv.15-19. The double occurrence (conquest story + city list) reflects two different source types being combined in the chapter: a narrative tradition and an administrative record, both preserving genuine historical memory.</p>",
    "50": "<p>Anab, Eshtemoh, Anim — Anab means 'grape(s),' a name reflecting the vine-growing potential of the Judean hill country. Eshtemoh was a Levitical city (Josh 21:14; 1 Sam 30:28) — among the places David sent portions of Amalek's spoil after Ziklag. The Levitical cities within the hill country dispersed priestly presence throughout Judah's heartland.</p>",
    "51": "<p>Goshen, Holon, Giloh — Giloh is listed in 2 Sam 15:12 as the hometown of Ahithophel, David's chief counselor who defected to Absalom's rebellion. The allotment geography reaches into David's court: the most dangerous betrayal David ever faced came from a man whose home town is mapped in Joshua's distribution of the hill country.</p>",
    "52": "<p>Arab, Dumah, Eshan — the southern hill country. Dumah later appears in Isa 21:11 as a prophecy against Edom; the place name's association with silence or desolation (Hebrew <em>dûmāh</em> = silence) may have shaped the Isaiah passage's wordplay.</p>",
    "53": "<p>Janum, Beth-tappuah, Aphekah — the central hill country continues. Beth-tappuah ('house of apples') suggests orchard-centered settlement; the Judean highlands were known for their fruit production in antiquity, and place names often recorded the agricultural character of their sites.</p>",
    "54": "<p>Humtah, Kiriath-arba/Hebron, Zior — Hebron appears in the city list under its pre-conquest name Kiriath-arba (v.54 = Hebron of ch.14:15). This is not an error but an acknowledgment that even after Caleb's conquest, the city retained its ancient name in administrative records. Hebron was Abraham's burial site (Gen 23), Jacob's home base (Gen 37:14), and David's first capital (2 Sam 2:1) — its weight in Israelite memory is unmatched.</p>",
    "55": "<p>Maon, Carmel, Ziph, Juttah — this cluster was David's wilderness territory during the Saul period. Nabal lived at Maon and grazed flocks at Carmel (1 Sam 25:2); David's confrontation with Nabal and marriage to Abigail occurred in this precise landscape. The allotment maps the terrain of later biblical narrative with striking precision.</p>",
    "56": "<p>Jezreel, Jokdeam, Zanoah — a different Jezreel from the famous northern valley; this is a Judahite Jezreel in the southern hill country. The duplication of place names (two Jezreels, two Hebrons, multiple Mizpehs) reflects independent regional naming traditions that the consolidated tribal records preserved without harmonization.</p>",
    "57": "<p>Kain, Gibeah, Timnah — Timnah appears as Samson's wife's hometown (Judg 14:1-2), located in the Sorek Valley at the Judah-Philistine border zone; the Samson narratives unfold in the exact territory mapped in this city list.</p>",
    "58": "<p>Halhul, Beth-zur, Gedor — Beth-zur is the site of a significant Maccabean battle (1 Macc 4:29) in the second century BCE; its fortification by Rehoboam (2 Chr 11:7) shows its strategic importance as a hill country fortress controlling access from the Shephelah. The allotment's city list reaches into the Hellenistic period.</p>",
    "59": "<p>Maarath, Beth-anoth, Eltekon — six cities in this sub-group. The hill country list encompasses the entire central ridge from south (Negev frontier) to north (Jerusalem approaches), systematically surveying what was and would become the heartland of the Judean monarchy.</p>",
    "60": "<p>Kiriath-baal/Kiriath-jearim, Rabbah — two cities in this group. Kiriath-jearim is the former Gibeonite city (Josh 9:17) where the ark rested for twenty years (1 Sam 7:1-2); its Baal-name (<em>qiryat-baʿal</em>) is an ancient name preserved alongside its later one, showing how city names accumulated layers of meaning. The ark's twenty-year residence at Kiriath-jearim is one of the most neglected stretches of Israelite history.</p>",
    "61": "<p>The wilderness zone — the Judean Desert between the hill country and the Dead Sea. This barren terrain was Israel's place of refuge, prayer, and testing: David hid from Saul in its caves (1 Sam 23-24; Ps 63's inscription places it here), the Qumran community later settled its shores, and John the Baptist preached in this wilderness. Its six cities are minor outposts in harsh terrain.</p>",
    "62": "<p>En-gedi — 'spring of the kid' — is the most significant wilderness city: an oasis of freshwater springs on the western Dead Sea shore, surrounded by dramatic cliffs. David hid in En-gedi's caves (1 Sam 23:29; 24:1); the Song of Songs uses En-gedi's henna blossoms as an image of the beloved (Song 1:14). Its inclusion in the city list connects the administrative record to the ecological reality of the Judean desert: one reliable water source in six wilderness towns.</p>",
    "63": "<p>Jerusalem's Jebusites — the most significant failure notice in Judah's allotment. Jerusalem (<em>yĕrûšālaim</em>) was a Jebusite city-state with natural defenses (narrow ridge, steep valleys on three sides) that made it nearly impregnable to ancient assault techniques. It remained Jebusite not only through the conquest but through the entire period of the judges (Judg 1:21 repeats this notice). David captures it by stealth through the water tunnel (<em>ṣinnôr</em>, 2 Sam 5:8) — a military innovation that bypassed the city's defensive walls. The city's non-Israelite status made it a politically neutral capital: it belonged to no tribe, so David could make it his own without alienating any tribe in favor of another.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>The Joseph tribes' allotment begins from the Jordan at Jericho — the logical starting point since Jericho was the entry point into Canaan and the territorial pivot between Benjamin (to the south) and Ephraim (to the north). The spring of Jericho (<em>mê yĕrîḥô</em>) was the primary water source for the Jordan valley town; controlling it meant controlling access to the interior valleys.</p>",
    "2": "<p>From Bethel/Luz to the Archite border at Ataroth. Bethel is the primary northern landmark: Jacob's dream-site (Gen 28:19), Abraham's altar-site (Gen 12:8), the site of Jeroboam's golden calf (1 Kgs 12:29). Its position at the boundary between Ephraim and Benjamin reflects its role as a contested religious and political center throughout the monarchic period — both tribes claimed association with it.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The western boundary descends through Japhletite territory to Lower Beth-horon and Gezer. Beth-horon Upper and Lower are the sites of Joshua's pursuit in ch.10:10-11; the passes were strategically critical as the main descent from the hill country to the coastal plain. Gezer's appearance here as the western terminus of Ephraim's territory sets up the crucial failure notice at v.10 — the western boundary was theoretically claimed but practically unoccupied.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'So Manasseh and Ephraim received their inheritance.' This brief summary verse marks the end of the collective Joseph allotment description before the chapter details Ephraim's specific portion. The joint description (vv.1-3) reflects the historical reality that Ephraim and Manasseh were not always clearly distinguished in early settlement patterns; the administrative separation into two distinct tribal territories was a later consolidation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Ephraim's eastern boundary runs from Ataroth-addar to Upper Beth-horon. The Ataroth-addar/Beth-horon line formed the border between Ephraim and Benjamin (Josh 18:13). The closeness of these boundaries to Jerusalem explains why Benjamin's and Ephraim's histories are intertwined: Saul (Benjaminite) and Joshua (Ephraimite) were effectively neighbors.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The northern boundary reaches Michmash — famous as the site of Jonathan's single-handed assault on the Philistine garrison (1 Sam 13-14). The Michmash pass was the primary northern approach to the central hill country; its fortification by the Philistines and its liberation by Jonathan are played out in the allotment geography. The boundary continues to the Jordan on the east.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Janoah, Ataroth, Naarah to Jericho — Ephraim's eastern boundary descends from the hill country to the Jordan valley. Naarah ('na'aran' in 1 Chr 7:28) is unidentified but part of the eastern Jordan valley settlements. The boundary terminates at the Jordan, making the river Ephraim's eastern wall.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Kanah Ravine (Wadi Qana) forms Ephraim's western boundary, running from Tappuah to the sea. The Kanah Ravine is an actual geographic feature in the central Shephelah, identifiable today. The river/wadi system as a boundary reflects common ANE administrative practice: natural watercourses were unambiguous, perennial boundary markers.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Some cities were set apart for Ephraim within the territory of Manasseh.' This administrative oddity — Ephraimite cities embedded in Manassite territory — reflects the settlement reality of the central highlands: the two Joseph tribes' settlements were geographically intermingled. The administrative boundary drawn in this chapter is a legal idealization of a settlement pattern that was actually more complex and interwoven.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Gezer failure notice: 'the Ephraimites did not drive out the Canaanites living in Gezer.' Gezer was a major Bronze Age city-state (Tell el-Jazari) whose Canaanite rulers had maintained Egyptian vassal status; its population and fortifications made it resistant to Israelite conquest. Archaeological excavations at Gezer confirm Late Bronze Age occupation continuing without destruction into the Iron Age I period. The Canaanites were subjected to <em>mas</em> (forced/corvée labor) instead — a compromise that preserved Canaanite urban expertise while asserting Israelite political authority. This forced-labor arrangement became a template for Solomon's later labor levies (1 Kgs 9:15-21); Gezer itself was eventually burned by Pharaoh and given as a dowry to Solomon's Egyptian wife (1 Kgs 9:16-17).</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>Machir, the firstborn of Manasseh, is given Gilead and Bashan (the trans-Jordan portion). The identification of Machir as a 'man of war' who had already taken Gilead explains why his descendants received the less-settled trans-Jordan territory — they were equipped militarily for it. Machir's descendants later appear as Mephibosheth's protectors (2 Sam 9:4-5; 17:27), maintaining a trans-Jordan presence into the Davidic period.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Cisjordan Manassites are distributed by clan: Abiezer, Helek, Asriel, Shechem, Hepher, Shemida. These clan names appear in the Samaria Ostraca (eighth century BCE administrative dockets from the northern kingdom), confirming that these were real administrative divisions in the later Israelite state — the allotment's clan-level organization persisted for centuries into the monarchy.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Zelophehad's daughters — Mahlah, Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, Tirzah — invoke a legal precedent already established in Num 27:1-11 and ratified with additional conditions in Num 36:1-12. The original case arose from Zelophehad's death without male heirs; YHWH's ruling (Num 27:7-8) established women's inheritance rights when there are no sons. The application in Joshua shows the allotment process operating under formal case law — the daughters' claim is not a novelty but the application of binding legal precedent.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'They appeared before Eleazar the priest, Joshua son of Nun, and the leaders' — the formal judicial forum, the same three-party body that oversees all the allotments (Josh 14:1; 19:51). The daughters' citation of the specific YHWH-to-Moses ruling (Num 27:7) demonstrates legal literacy: they know the applicable law and cite it correctly. Their inheritance was granted 'as the LORD commanded Moses' — the allotment process is a judicial one where legal precedent is authoritative.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Manasseh received ten portions: five male clan portions (v.2) plus five female portions from Zelophehad's five daughters. This arithmetic is unusual — normally a tribe receives one block of territory — and reflects the complexity of the Manasseh clan structure (split between trans-Jordan and Cisjordan; daughters inheriting alongside sons). The number ten may also reflect a fuller administrative list not fully preserved in vv.1-6.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Manasseh's daughters inherited among his sons' — a formal statement affirming the daughters' full inheritance status alongside male heirs. This was not the cultural default in the ancient Near East (Mesopotamian law codes generally favored male heirs, with daughters receiving dowry instead of inheritance); the Israelite case law represented in Num 27 and applied here was distinctive in recognizing daughters' inheritance claims when no sons existed.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Manasseh's western boundary runs from Asher to Michmethath (facing Shechem). Shechem is the chapter's geographic anchor — the most important city in Manasseh's territory, already the site of Jacob's altar (Gen 33:18-20), Joseph's bones burial (Josh 24:32), and the covenant renewal (Josh 24:1). Its position at the center of the boundary description reflects its central role in Israelite religious and political life.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Tappuah — the city belonged to Manasseh but the land of Tappuah on Manasseh's border belonged to Ephraim. This administrative split (city in one tribe, surrounding agricultural land in another) reflects the complexity of settlement-era land tenure. Cities and their agricultural hinterlands were not always administered as a unit; the allotment process distinguished between the fortified urban center and the surrounding fields and villages.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The Kanah Ravine (same as ch.16:8) separates Ephraim from Manasseh; Ephraimite cities north of the ravine within Manasseh's territory again reflect the settlement intermingling noted in 16:9. The Kanah/Wadi Qana was a real geographic boundary used consistently in both tribal descriptions — confirmation that these chapters derive from actual survey data.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ephraim to the south, Manasseh to the north, the sea on the west — the basic tribal geography of the central highlands. Their junction at Asher and Issachar to the north sets up the transition to the northern allotments in ch.19. The central highlands were the Joseph tribes' heartland; the northern valleys (Jezreel, Beth-shean) remained Canaanite (Josh 17:11-12), separating the central hill country from the Galilee tribes.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Manasseh's possession within Issachar and Asher: Beth-shean, Ibleam, Dor, En-dor, Taanach, Megiddo — and their 'three heights' (or 'Naphoth-dor'). This is the most strategically important city list in the allotment chapters: Beth-shean controlled the Jordan valley / Jezreel junction; Megiddo controlled the Carmel pass into the Jezreel Valley; Taanach guarded the same approaches. All six cities — the major fortresses of the Jezreel and Beth-shean valleys — are listed as Manasseh's possession and immediately noted (v.12) as unconquered.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'The Manassites were unable to drive out the people of those towns' — the failure notice for the entire Jezreel-Beth-shean valley zone. The archaeological record confirms continued Canaanite occupation at Beth-shean (Egyptian-administered through the Late Bronze Age), Megiddo, and Taanach throughout Iron Age I. The 'inability' was not merely military reluctance but a real technological disparity: Canaanite chariot forces in the flat valleys were strategically superior to Israelite infantry.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'When the Israelites grew stronger, they subjected the Canaanites to forced labor but did not drive them out completely.' The trajectory — military incapacity → political domination via labor conscription — is identical to Ephraim's arrangement at Gezer (16:10). Forced labor (<em>mas</em>) became the characteristic Israelite response to unconquerable Canaanite cities; it became the structural model for the Solomonic corvée that eventually provoked the northern secession (1 Kgs 5:13-14; 12:4,18).</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Why have you given us only one allotment and one portion? We are a numerous people.' The Joseph tribe's complaint reveals several tensions in the allotment process: (1) the lot-based system gave equal weight to all tribes regardless of population; (2) the Joseph tribes believed their demographic size entitled them to more territory; (3) the complaint implies dissatisfaction with what they have received — a contrast with Caleb's eagerness to take the hardest territory (ch.14:12). The social ethic of the allotment is egalitarian; the complaint reflects a different value system.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Joshua's reply: 'if you are such a great people, go up into the forest and clear land there in the territory of the Perizzites and Rephaim.' The 'forest' (<em>hayyāʿar</em>) in the central highlands of Ephraim and Manasseh is historically attested by pollen analysis: Iron Age I sites in the central hill country show significant deforestation, confirming that early Israelite settlers were literally clearing forest for terraced agriculture. Joshua's challenge is not rhetorical but practical — the unheld territory was wooded highland, not flat farmland. The Perizzites (forest-dwellers?) and Rephaim (giants) still needed clearing.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'The hill country is not enough, and all the Canaanites in the lowland have iron chariots.' Iron chariots (<em>rekeb barzel</em>) represent the decisive military technology of the Late Bronze / early Iron Age transition. Iron-fitted chariot wheels and fittings gave Canaanite forces in the flat valleys (Jezreel, Beth-shean) an overwhelming tactical advantage over Israelite infantry — iron could not be effectively worked by Israelites until after the Philistine period (1 Sam 13:19-22). The complaint is militarily honest: the hill country can be settled, but the valley floor cannot be taken by force until Israel achieves iron-working parity.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Joshua's counter: 'you are a great people and have great power — you will not have just one allotment.' The argument inverts the complaint: their greatness is the reason they can clear more territory, not the reason they deserve more granted territory. The distinction between claimed territory and cleared-and-settled territory is fundamental to the allotment theology: YHWH gives the title; Israel does the work of possession. Joshua's challenge is covenantal — great resources mean great responsibility to act on what has been given.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'The forested hill country will be yours; clear it, and it will be yours to its farthest limits.' This verse encapsulates the allotment's underlying principle: the land is given, but possession requires human effort and covenant obedience. The Canaanite iron chariots in the valley are not dismissed — 'you shall drive them out even though they have iron chariots and are strong.' The promise is not of an easy victory but of a certain one, contingent on Israel's engagement. The failure to take the valley cities (v.12-13) was a failure of will and covenant obedience, not a divine retraction of the promise.</p>"
  }
}


def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'joshua')
    merge_comm(existing, JOSHUA)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'joshua', existing)

    il = json.loads((ROOT / 'data/interlinear/joshua.json').read_text())
    all_ok = True
    for ch in range(15, 18):
        ck = str(ch)
        il_vv = set(il.get(ck, {}).keys())
        out_vv = set(existing.get(ck, {}).keys())
        missing = il_vv - out_vv
        if missing:
            print(f'ch {ch} MISSING: {sorted(missing, key=int)}')
            all_ok = False
        else:
            print(f'ch {ch}: complete ({len(out_vv)} verses)')
    if all_ok:
        print('All verses present ✓')
    chs = sorted(existing.keys(), key=int)
    print(f'Joshua mkt-context chapters now: {chs} ({len(chs)}/24)')


if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
